25|$|Numerous {{social forces}} {{led to a}} move for deinstitutionalization; {{researchers}} generally give credit to six main factors: criticisms of public <b>mental</b> <b>hospitals,</b> incorporation of mind-altering drugs in treatment, support from President Kennedy for federal policy changes, shifts to community-based care, changes in public perception, and individual states' desires to reduce costs from <b>mental</b> <b>hospitals.</b>|$|E
25|$|The anti-psychiatry {{movement}} {{coming to}} the fore in the 1960s has opposed many of the practices, conditions, or existence of <b>mental</b> <b>hospitals.</b> The psychiatric consumer/survivor movement has often objected to or campaigned against conditions in <b>mental</b> <b>hospitals</b> or their use, voluntarily or involuntarily. The mental patient liberation movement emphatically opposes involuntary treatment but generally {{does not have any}} issue with any psychiatric treatments that are consensual, provided that both parties are free to withdraw consent at any time.|$|E
